  <mainDescription>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Business_Levels&quot; name=&quot;XE_Business_Levels&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The figure below illustrates the structure of a fictitious company. In addition to the normal &quot;corporate service&quot; (i.e.&#xD;
    HR, etc.) it has three business lines, namely:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Railroad Products Division&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Recreational Products Division&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Aerospace Products Division&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;center&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt='The structure of an enterprise with three &quot;business lines&quot; and various &quot;business domains&quot;'&#xD;
    src=&quot;./resources/Business-line-domain.png&quot; width=&quot;469&quot; height=&quot;432&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Within each Business Line (and also within &quot;Corporate Administration&quot;) we find the typical Business Domains, namely&#xD;
    Marketing &amp;amp; Sales, HR and Finance. A Business Domain could therefore be equated to a &quot;vertical market&quot; in the&#xD;
    software/systems services sense of the word. We therefore have the possibility of a number of different IT Architects&#xD;
    within the enterprise, at each of these &quot;levels&quot;, namely:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Enterprise Architect&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Line Architects&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Business Domain Architects&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The need for all of these different IT architects within the enterprise is obviously dependent upon the size of the&#xD;
    enterprise, and to some extent the type of activity within the enterprise or business line.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Within each of these three levels of IT Architecture there are IT implementation projects, which need to have IT&#xD;
    Architect involvement; &lt;em>Project IT Architects&lt;/em>. Finally, depending upon the size of Business Domains, there may&#xD;
    be a need to have Business Unit IT Architects that focus on a small (but important or complex) portion of the Business&#xD;
    Domain.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In summary, a Business (enterprise) is composed of Business Lines, which are further sub-divided into Business Domains&#xD;
    (as is &quot;Corporate Administration&quot;), and which may be further sub-divided into Business Units. Each of the sub-division&#xD;
    will have IT implementation projects that need Project IT Architects assigned.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
